    // satisfy nums[i_j] = j.
    // Let the original indices of the selected elements be p_0, p_1, ..., p_{k-1}, where p_0 < p_1 < ... < p_{k-1}.
    // In the resulting array, the element from nums[p_j] is at index j.
    // We want this element to be a fixed point, so we need nums[p_j] = j.
    // We are looking for the longest sequence of indices p_0 < p_1 < ... < p_{k-1} such that nums[p_j] = j for all j=0, ..., k-1.

    // This is a variation of the Longest Increasing Subsequence problem, but simpler.
    // We are essentially trying to find the longest subsequence where the values match the required index in the subsequence.

    // We can iterate through the original array and greedily select elements that satisfy the condition.
    var count = 0 // This represents the target index 'j' in the resulting array (0, 1, 2, ...)

    for (i in 0 until n) {
        // If we keep nums[i], it will be placed at the next available position, which is 'count'.
        // For it to be a fixed point at this new position, we need nums[i] == count.
        if (nums[i] == count.toLong()) {
            count++
        }
    }

